2. 8-WEEK THEME ARC
==================================================
 
Theme structure: 4 themes × 2 weeks each.
Each theme builds on the previous one.
Week numbering is continuous — C2 runs Weeks 9–16.
 
Weeks 9–10: Reactions
  Focus: Reacting emotionally and naturally to what someone says —
  the first step in replacing "I see." with something real.
  Key phrases:
    Work:    "Oh wow, nice!" / "That's great!" / "Oh really?!"
             / "Seriously?!"
    Hobby:   "No way!" / "Oh that's so cool!" / "Really?!" / "Oh wow!"
    Travel:  "No way!" / "That's amazing!" / "Oh wow!" / "Seriously?!"
    Casual:  "Oh my gosh!" / "No way!" / "That's so cool!" / "Right?!"
  Grammar:  Reaction openers — "Oh" as a natural response marker (Wk 9);
            "No way!" and "Really?!" as authentic backchannels (Wk 10)
  Vocabulary: reaction words and exclamations per purpose (Wk 9 Day 3)
              energy-matching responses (Wk 10 Day 3)
  By end of Week 10: student can react with genuine emotion instead of
  "I see."
 
Weeks 11–12: Follow-up questions
  Focus: Asking a specific question after reacting — moving from one
  line of response to two.
  Key phrases:
    Work:    "What happened?" / "How did it go?" / "What did they say?"
             / "Did it work out?"
    Hobby:   "What made you want to try it?" / "How did you find it?"
             / "What was the best part?" / "Are you going back?"
    Travel:  "Where did you go?" / "What was it like?" / "Was it worth it?"
             / "What did you eat?"
    Casual:  "Tell me more!" / "How long did that take?" / "Was it fun?"
             / "Who did you go with?"
  Grammar:  "What happened?" — past tense question structure (Wk 11);
            "How did it go?" — open question pattern (Wk 12)
  Vocabulary: follow-up question starters per context (Wk 11 Day 3)
              deeper interest words (Wk 12 Day 3)
  By end of Week 12: student can react AND ask a follow-up question
 
Weeks 13–14: Showing genuine interest
  Focus: Verbal signals that show the other person you are listening
  and care — what native speakers call "active listening."
  Key phrases:
    Work:    "Oh interesting!" / "I didn't know that!" / "That makes
             sense!" / "I totally get that."
    Hobby:   "I totally get that!" / "Right?!" / "That's exactly how
             I felt!" / "Same here!"
    Travel:  "Oh I've heard of that!" / "Is it as good as they say?"
             / "I need to try that!" / "That sounds incredible!"
    Casual:  "Oh same!" / "I know exactly what you mean!" / "Right?!"
             / "Honestly, same."
  Grammar:  "I totally get that" — empathy phrases (Wk 13);
            "That makes sense" — validation phrases (Wk 14)
  Vocabulary: Spaced Recall Day on Week 13 Day 3 (no new vocab —
              retrieves Wks 9–12 phrases from memory)
  By end of Week 14: student shows active listening, not just answering
 
Weeks 15–16: Full conversational flow
  Focus: Connecting reactions + follow-up questions + genuine interest
  signals into a continuous 5–7 line conversation without long silences.
  Key structure: Greeting → they share something → you react → you ask
  → they answer → you show interest → natural close
  Key phrases: All previous C2 phrases combined into full exchanges
  Grammar:  The 3-part C2 conversation formula (Wk 16 Day 2):
            1. React: "Oh really?! / No way!"
            2. Ask: "What happened? / How did it go?"
            3. Connect: "I totally get that. / That makes sense."
  Vocabulary: Spaced Recall Day on Week 15 Day 3 (no new vocab —
              retrieves Wks 9–14 phrases from memory);
              Full C2 vocabulary toolkit summary on Week 16 Day 3
  By end of Week 16: student can sustain a 5–7 line conversation
 
 
