9. CONTENT NOTES & DECISIONS
==================================================
 
THE CORE C2 PATTERN — REACT THEN ASK
--------------------------------------
Every prompt in C2 must model or reinforce this two-step pattern:
 
  Step 1: React with genuine emotion
    "Oh really?!" / "No way!" / "That's amazing!" / "Seriously?!"
 
  Step 2: Ask a specific follow-up question immediately
    "What happened?" / "How did it go?" / "Was it worth it?"
 
This pattern must appear in Day 1 dialogues (modelled), Day 2 grammar
tips (explained), Day 4 prompts (scaffolded practice), Day 5 quizzes
(contrast with flat response), Day 6 scenarios (applied in real context),
and Day 7 free speaking (autonomous use without reminders).
 
The two steps ALWAYS appear together — never just a reaction alone, and
never just a question without the emotional reaction that precedes it.
Students who produce "Oh really? What happened?" have achieved the goal.
Students who produce "What happened?" without the reaction have not.
 
 
REACTION CALIBRATION BY REGISTER
-----------------------------------
Reactions must be calibrated to the register of each purpose:
 
  Work (professional-casual):
    Use: "Oh wow, nice!" / "That's great!" / "Seriously?!" / "Oh really?!"
    Avoid: "Oh my gosh!" (too casual for most workplaces)
    Note: Reactions in work settings should be warm but slightly contained.
    "Oh wow, that's great!" is better than "OH WOW NO WAY!" at work.
 
  Hobby (friendly-casual):
    Use: "No way!" / "Oh that's so cool!" / "Really?!" / "Amazing!"
    Full range of casual reactions is appropriate.
 
  Travel (friendly-casual):
    Use: "No way!" / "That's amazing!" / "Oh wow, seriously?!"
    Travellers bond over shared enthusiasm — big reactions are natural.
 
  Casual (informal-casual):
    Use: "Oh my gosh!" / "No way!" / "That's so cool!" / "Right?!"
    Most expressive register — all casual reactions are fair game.
 
 
WEEK 9 DAY 1 — FIRST C2 PROMPT (IMPORTANT)
--------------------------------------------
The Week 9 Day 1 prompt is the student's first message after completing
8 weeks of C1. Unlike C1 Week 1 Day 1, there is no full goal summary
or elaborate scaffolding. The prompt should:
1. Acknowledge the transition without making it heavy
2. Show (in the modelled dialogue) the new C2 skill clearly
3. Include a prior knowledge bridge in Japanese support — brief and
   energising, not lengthy
 
A suggested bridge note for Japanese support (all purposes adapt this):
">> Competency 1（はじめの一歩）お疲れ様でした！自然な挨拶・本音の答え・
質問の返し方・短い会話 — ここまでできるようになりましたね。
今週からはその会話を「続ける」練習をします。相手が何か話したとき、
どう反応するか — これがCompetency 2のテーマです！"
 
 
QUIZ FORMAT CONSISTENCY
------------------------
C2 quizzes contrast a natural React + Ask response against a flat or
unnatural response. The wrong answer in quizzes ALWAYS represents the
common Super Beginner failure mode:
- "I see." (flat, conversation-ending)
- "That's good." (minimal, no follow-up)
- "Oh, okay." (acknowledgement without engagement)
- Formal/stiff versions: "I am glad to hear that."
 
This contrast teaches students to recognise (and avoid) the exact habits
that C2 is designed to break.
 
 
REAL TALK SCENARIOS (DAY 6) — C2 DESIGN RULE
----------------------------------------------
All Day 6 scenarios in C2 must open with the other person sharing
INFORMATION or NEWS — not a question. This forces the student to
react and ask, rather than just answer.
 
Wrong framing: "Your coworker asks: 'How was your weekend?'"
  (This is a C1 scenario — answering a question.)
 
Correct framing: "Your coworker says: 'I just finished a huge project!'"
  (This is a C2 scenario — reacting to news.)
 
The student cannot hide behind a prepared answer — they must produce
a genuine reaction and a follow-up question in the moment.
 
 
WEEK 16 DAY 7 — MODULE FINAL CHALLENGE
----------------------------------------
The final prompt should mirror C1 Week 8 Day 7 in format — a free,
unscripted conversation challenge — with:
- A setup that delivers news/information from the conversation partner
- No script, no examples, no help
- Metacognitive reflection questions in Japanese (two questions —
  same as C1 Competency 1 final, adapted for C2 skills)
- Simplified achievement checklist in Japanese:
  ✓ 自然な反応ができる（Oh really?! / No way!）
  ✓ 相手の話を聞いてから質問が返せる（What happened? / How did it go?）
  ✓ 本当に聞いていることを示せる（I totally get that / Right?!）
  ✓ 5〜7行の自然な会話ができる
 
